\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Opening Verse — Dva Suparna}
\thispagestyle{plain}
\vspace*{-0.4cm}
\begin{center}
{\devafont\Large द्वा सुपर्णा सयुजा सखाया समानं वृक्षं परिषस्वजाते ।}\\[0.7em]
{\devafont\Large तयोरन्यः पिप्पलं स्वाद्वत्त्यनश्नन्नन्यो अभिचाकशीति ॥}\\[0.7em]
\end{center}
\vspace{1em}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.2em, itemsep=0.25em]
  \item Dva Suparna: Two birds with beautiful wings.
  \item Sayuja Sakhaya: Inseparable companions and friends.
  \item Samanam Vriksham: Dwelling on the same tree.
  \item Parishasvajate: Are perched/embracing the tree.
  \item Tayo Anya: Of the two, one (the individual soul).
  \item Pippalam Svadu Atti: Eats the fruit (of the tree) with relish.
  \item Anyah Anasnan: The other, without eating.
  \item Abhichakashiti: Merely looks on as a witness.
\end{itemize}
\vspace{0.6em}
\noindent\textbf{The Metaphorical Symbolism:}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.4em, itemsep=0.35em]
  \item The Tree: Represents the Body or the material world (Prakriti).
  \item The First Bird (Jivatma): Represents the Individual Soul or the Ego. This bird is busy eating the fruits of the tree—some sweet (pleasure) and some bitter (pain). It is deeply involved in the world and affected by its joys and sorrows.
  \item The Second Bird (Paramatma): Represents the Supreme Soul or Pure Consciousness. This bird sits on a higher branch, calm and silent. It does not eat the fruit; it simply watches the first bird. It is the eternal witness (Sakshi), unaffected by the world. The Philosophical LessonThe Upanishad explains that as long as the first bird (the person) identifies with the "eating" (the actions and results), it remains anxious and unhappy. However, the moment it looks up, recognizes the second bird, and realizes that its true nature is actually that of the silent witness, it becomes free from grief and attains liberation (Moksha).
\end{enumerate}
\end{multicols}
\newpage

\section*{Blessed Moments with Daaji}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Blessed Moments with Daaji}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent Meditation has transformed my life in a beautiful and meaningful way. Under the blessings and guidance of Daaji, I discovered greater peace, balance, and clarity in my thoughts, behaviour, and lifestyle. This inner journey slowly reflected in every part of my life — in my routine business, my love for birding, and my passion for photography. Nature began to speak more deeply to my heart, and every moment became a lesson in mindfulness and gratitude. Through meditation, I learned to live with patience, compassion, and simplicity. In every step of my journey, I continue to seek the blessings of Daaji, whose wisdom inspires me to walk through life with harmony, joy, and inner peace.

\end{multicols}
\attribphoto{height=3cm}{daaj.jpeg}{Written by: P. Radhakrishna Pai\\(Mathru Kripa)}
\newpage

\section*{My Journey of Photography}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{My Journey of Photography}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent My interest in photography began with beautiful stories and curiosity. After completing my education, I used to visit Geetha Studio near our shop in Vittal every day. The studio was owned by Late Mr. Keshava Nayak and Late Madhumathi Akka. Watching them work kindled my passion — slowly, I learned the basics of photography, film developing, and printing in dark rooms. Those were the days of black and white photos, and digital cameras were unheard of — photography was all about patience and light. Later, I joined our grocery wholesale and retail business, and my photography passion paused for nearly forty years.

One day, my childhood friend Mr. Keshava Vittla, a talented photo journalist who had worked for many leading newspapers and also ran his own studio, visited me. One of his relatives had opened a new studio in Vittal and wanted to sell a Canon DSLR camera. He encouraged me to buy it, and I agreed. That moment marked the rebirth of my photographic journey.

Slowly, I began capturing again, upgraded my cameras and lenses, and improved my skills. A friend then suggested me to open a Facebook account, where I started posting my photos of birds. Day by day, the likes and appreciation I received from people inspired me to move my hobby to the next level. Through this, I made many birding and photography friends across India and the world.

In my early days, I didn't know much about birds or their habitats. One day, after I posted a picture of a bird, Mr. Shiva Shankar from Karkala commented with the correct name. Later, he gifted me his book "Birds of Coastal Karnataka" — filled with his own photographs. That book became a great guide and motivation for me.

Even today, I continue this beautiful journey. I've learned that photography is not just about clicking pictures — it's about capturing memories, building friendship, and connecting deeply with nature.

\end{multicols}
\attribution{Written by: P. Radhakrishna Pai\\(Mathru Kripa)}
\newpage

\section*{My Family and Our Legacy}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{My Family and Our Legacy}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent My father, Late P. Janardhan Pai, and my mother, Late Smt. Bharathi Pai, are the foundation and inspiration of my life. My father started our business journey at the young age of sixteen, from zero, with hard work, honesty, and strong determination. Through his dedication, he built a respected business empire in Vittal.

Along with being a visionary businessman, he was also a writer in Kannada, a man of charity, and a pillar of society. His greatest ambition was to support education, especially the government school in Vittal, healthcare, and temple development in our hometown, .

Together, as a family, we worked to fulfil all his noble dreams, creating permanent projects in schools, hospitals, and temples that continue to benefit the community.

My mother, Late Smt. Bharathi Pai, was the divine strength behind our family — a goddess in human form. Her love, patience, and endless care has been our greatest blessing. She was a perfect homemaker and the emotional backbone of our family, supporting all good deeds and encouraging every step of progress.

I am blessed with a loving family of my own. My wife, Smt. Anuradha Pai, is my lovely life partner and constant source of encouragement — she stands by me at every moment with care and understanding.

We are blessed with twin daughters, Shraddha and Shreya, who have grown into graceful, well-educated, and cultured women. They both got married to twin brothers — Sanketh Phadnis and Saurabh Phadnis, and are now well settled in Mumbai with the blessings of my parents.

My younger brother Subraya Pai, and my sisters Smt. Kalpana Nayak and Smt. Shubhakiran Shenoy, have always been pillars of love and support. Together, our family stands as one — built on faith, values, and gratitude.

Truly, I owe everything to my parents and family, whose blessings guide every step of my life.

\end{multicols}
\attribution{Written by: P. Radhakrishna Pai\\(Mathru Kripa)}
\newpage

\section*{From My Twin Daughters}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{From My Twin Daughters}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent Growing up, we have always known our father as a man of many passions. Long before this beautiful collection of birds and photographs came into being, he was someone who found joy in creativity — whether through photography, painting or lovingly crafting our family's Ganesh Chaturthi idols each year. Creativity was never just a hobby for him, it was simply a part of who he was.

In our childhood years, responsibilities came first. With the weight of family and business duties on his shoulders, much of his time was devoted to ensuring stability and security, taking care of everyone around him. Yet, even during those busy years, his curiosity for the world and his love for nature quietly remained alive within him. After the demise of his father, as life slowly allowed him moments of pause and personal time, he began returning to his passion — photography with renewed dedication. What started as small moments carved out of a busy routine gradually transformed into a journey of patience, discovery and deep connection with nature.

Behind this journey has always stood our mother, constant pillar of support. In the early days, she would sit at the shop so he could step away to photograph birds and wildlife, encouraging him to pursue what brought him happiness. Her belief in his passion gave his dreams the space to grow. Today, it is heartwarming to see how their journey has evolved from quiet support to shared adventures, with both of them now exploring forests, landscapes and the beauty of nature together. Listening to her speak about these experiences and the joy she finds in them makes us realize how passions, when nurtured, bring happiness not just to one person but to an entire family.

To the world, this book may be a remarkable collection of bird photography — a showcase of patience, skill and artistic vision. But to us, it tells a deeper story. It reflects a man who has always been an all-rounder, balancing duty with dreams, family with personal passion, and responsibility with creativity. Beyond his many talents, he is also someone who finds joy in the simple warmth of home. The way he steps into the kitchen to help our mother, taking time to cook and lovingly preparing delicious dishes for us, is just another glimpse of the care and affection he pours into family life. Moments like these make us realize how beautifully he embodies the qualities of a perfect family man ,someone who blends dedication, creativity, love and warmth so effortlessly.

As his children, we have witnessed the sincerity he brings to everything he does. He has taught us, not through words but through example, the importance of following what brings joy, making time for oneself and pursuing passions regardless of life's stages.

Today, as we see both our parents embracing this phase of life — free from earlier responsibilities and finally taking time for themselves ,our hearts are filled with pride and happiness. Watching them do what they truly love, exploring nature together and finding joy in simple moments, is perhaps the greatest reward for all the years they devoted to family.

This book is more than a collection of photographs, it is a reflection of patience, passion and a lifelong love for nature. As his daughters, we feel immense pride in celebrating not only his talent but the person he is — loving, dedicated, and endlessly inspiring.

With love and admiration,

We wish him continued joy, success and countless more flights of discovery through the world of birds and beyond.

\end{multicols}
\attribphoto{height=3cm}{twinsister.jpeg}{Written by: Shraddha Pai Phadnis and Shreya Pai Phadnis}
\newpage

\section*{My Life Partner}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{My Life Partner}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent It’s a very special and emotional moment for me. I feel incredibly happy and proud that my husband has written a book on his bird photography journey—what began as a simple hobby has grown into his passion and a beautiful expression of his deep love for nature.

He started this journey nearly 15–16 years ago. In those early days, when he would go out with his friends for photography, I used to feel a little upset. After our marriage, we were not just partners, but the best of friends, doing everything together. So when his weekends slowly became dedicated to birding trips, I often found myself feeling lonely. But today, my heart is filled only with pride and admiration. I have witnessed his dedication, his growth, and the quiet determination with which he followed his passion. What amazes me the most is this—he may not have patience for many things in life, but when it comes to waiting for birds, it is endless patience. That patience, that love, and that commitment is what has brought him to this moment.“A birder in true sense” This book is not just about photography; it is a reflection of his journey, his perseverance, and his love for the natural world.

I am truly proud of you.

\end{multicols}
\attribution{With Love\\Anuradha Pai}
\newpage

\section*{My Elder Brother’s Endeavour}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{My Elder Brother’s Endeavour}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent It is a feeling of privilege to write about my elder brother, Radhakrishna Pai’s passion towards bird photography. I remember the words of my Guru, where he once said that we should all chase a hobby which will ultimately help us in our fifties to lead a balanced life. Being a busy man, running multiple family owned businesses while simultaneously chasing his passion and hobbies is not an easy task. But my brother is able to find time for both with fine balance. I truly appreciate his photography journey, it is one that makes him a true lover of nature and fuels his growth as a refined human being. Hearty congratulations to him on his maiden book release on the eve of his successful completion of sixty years. My sincere prayers to Almighty to bless him with tons of happiness, health ,success and prosperity in the coming years, with lots of time to pursue his hobbies and passion.

\end{multicols}
\attribphoto{width=3cm}{subra.jpeg}{P. Subraya Pai}
\newpage

\section*{Moments Across Miles}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Moments Across Miles}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent During my birding and photography journey, I have been fortunate to capture more than 1000 different species of birds and animals from all over India — and even from the wild plains of Maasai Mara, Kenya, Tanzania, and South Africa.

Along with wildlife, I have also photographed temples, landscapes, and the beauty of nature through my lens.

In this first book, I have chosen to present some of my most memorable bird photographs along with a few animal images from Maasai Mara. Each frame holds a story — of patience, learning, and love for the wild.

I humbly request you to share this book with your friends and family, and above all, to respect nature and love all living beings. Places visited for bird photography almost all places of Karnataka, including Ranganathittu, Kokkare Bellur, Hesaraghatta, Maidanahalli (Blackbuck Reserve), Banavasi, Mundagod, Mulky, Mangalore, Bantwal, Alangar, Vittla, along with Kuduremukha, Durga WLS (Karkala), Kundapur, Coorg, Uttara Kannada and other places in India, like Tamil Nadu, Maharashtra, Uttarakhand, Kerala and Goa. Places visited outside India Maasai Mara (Tanzania), South Africa )

\end{multicols}
\attribution{— P. Radhakrishna Pai\\Mathru Kripa, Vittla}
\newpage

\section*{My Observation}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{My Observation}
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent In a world that often rushes by, where the cacophony of daily life drowns out the subtle whispers of nature, P. Radhakrishna Pai's journey into photography and connection with the avian world is something many of us might overlook.

Radhakrishna's narrative is not just about the technicalities of bird photography; it is a heartfelt exploration of passion, patience, and perseverance. From the early days of black-and-white photography in a modest studio to the vibrant colors of the digital age, his journey encapsulates the evolution of an artist who has remained true to his roots while embracing new challenges. It is a testament to the idea that it is never too late to pursue one's passions, and that the seeds of creativity, once sown, can flourish at any stage of life. Through his lens, Radhakrishna invites us to slow down and observe the intricate details of nature. (Each photograph tells a story, revealing the unique characteristics and behaviors of birds. ) (His ability to capture these moments reflects not only his technical skill but also his deep respect for the natural world).

Radhakrishna's interactions with fellow birders and nature enthusiasts showcase the sense of community that photography can foster. As you turn the pages of this book, may you find inspiration in Radhakrishna's journey. Let it encourage you to explore the beauty of your surroundings, to cultivate your passions, and to cherish the moments that nature provides. In a time where we often seek solace in screens, may his photographs serve as a bridge, connecting us to the extraordinary life that unfolds beyond our windows.

I am honored to present this collection, a true reflection of a life dedicated to photography and a heartfelt homage to the wonders of the natural world. May it inspire you to look closer, appreciate more, and perhaps even embark on your journey into the captivating realm of photography.

The story of P. Radhakrishna Pai's journey into photography encompasses several main themes:

\textbf{Passion and Inspiration} : The narrative illustrates how a childhood fascination can evolve into a lifelong passion. Radhakrishna's early experiences at Geetha Studio and the encouragement from friends reignite his interest in photography, showcasing the importance of inspiration in pursuing one's passions.

\textbf{Connection with Nature} : A significant theme is the deep bond between the photographer and the natural world, particularly with birds. Photography serves as a medium for Radhakrishna to connect with nature, highlighting the beauty and diversity of wildlife.

\textbf{Patience and Discipline} : Bird photography requires a great deal of patience and discipline, as Radhakrishna learns to wait for the perfect moment to capture images. This theme emphasizes the virtues necessary for both photography and life.

\textbf{Friendship and Community} : The story emphasizes the role of friendships in nurturing one's interests. Radhakrishna's connections with fellow photographers and mentors enrich his journey and create a sense of community around shared passions.

\textbf{Personal Growth and Learning} : Throughout the narrative, Radhakrishna reflects on his growth as a photographer and a person. His journey from a novice to a skilled photographer illustrates the importance of continuous learning and self-improvement.

\textbf{Memory and Legacy} : The act of capturing moments through photography serves as a way to preserve memories. Radhakrishna's decision to publish a book represents a desire to share his experiences and knowledge, leaving a legacy for future generations.

\textbf{Environmental Awareness} : Implicit in the story is a call for environmental consciousness. By showcasing the beauty of birds and nature, Radhakrishna encourages readers to appreciate and protect the natural world.

\textbf{Joy in Simplicity} : The narrative conveys the joy found in simple moments spent in nature. Radhakrishna's experiences reflect a philosophy of finding happiness in the little things, fostering a sense of gratitude and appreciation for life's fleeting moments.

\end{multicols}
\newpage
\begin{multicols}{2}
\noindent These themes collectively highlight the transformative power of photography and nature, illustrating how they can shape one’s identity, values, and connections with the world.

\end{multicols}
\attribphoto{width=3cm}{ullas_kamath.jpeg}{K. Ullas Kamath\\A relative, friend and an ardent admirer of dear Radhakrishna.}
