\section*{The Song of the Hills}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Song of the Hills}
\label{bird:1}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=11.5cm,keepaspectratio]{Vrathik2gb/Vrathik/6 s.jpg}\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent In the misty forests of Coorg, morning broke with the scent of coffee blossoms and the hum of life hidden among the trees. As sunlight filtered softly through

the canopy, the forest awoke in golden whispers.Amid this calm beauty, a gentle flutter caught my eye — the Yellow-browed Bulbul, perched gracefully on a mossy branch. Its bright yellow feathers glowed against the green, and its sweet, clear call echoed through the hills like a melody of joy.\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent It was pure poetry —

the blend of light, song and silence. It reminded me, that in Coorg, every sunrise carries a song, and every bird adds a note to nature's endless symphony.

\newpage

\section*{The Whispering Giant}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Whispering Giant}
\label{bird:2}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent In the leafy avenues of Mysore, where ancient trees tell stories of time, the morning air was filled with the fragrance of rain-soaked earth. As I looked up, sunlight streamed through the branches — and there it was, the Indian Grey Hornbill, perched high, calm and regal.

Its large curved bill and soft grey plumage blended beautifully with the old tree bark, a true guardian of the canopy. Every gentle movement, every call echoed with quiet strength — a reminder of how gracefully nature weaves majesty into simplicity.\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=11.5cm,keepaspectratio]{Vrathik2gb/Vrathik/frame_l_67.jpg}\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent This serene encounter in Mysore's green heart made me realize — some of nature's greatest wonders do not dazzle with color, but with their quiet dignity.

\newpage

\section*{The Grace of the Grasslands}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Grace of the Grasslands}
\label{bird:3}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=11.5cm,keepaspectratio]{Vrathik2gb/Vrathik/s16.jpg}\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent In the golden grasslands of Saswad, Maharashtra, the morning Sun painted the fields with a soft glow. Alongside my birding companion Datta Nagre, I scanned the open plains where wind and silence danced together.\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent Suddenly, out of the tall grass, rose a striking sight — the Crested Bunting (male), shining in deep black and chestnut tones, its tiny crest swaying gently in the breeze. It perched proudly on a dry stem, as if posing for the morning light itself.
Time paused — just the bird, the song of the wind, and the golden horizon! That elegant little bird reminded me that even the smallest life in nature carries the beauty and pride of creation.

\newpage

\section*{The Emerald Whisper}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Emerald Whisper}
\label{bird:4}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent In the lush green hills of Lathchapper, West Bengal, the morning mist drifted like silk through the forest. Alongside my birding friend Debpratim Shah, I followed the melody of unseen wings and the whisper of the wind through bamboo leaves.\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \begin{tikzpicture}\draw[dashed, line width=0.4pt, color=ink!35] (0,0) rectangle (12.0,-11.5);\node[anchor=center] at (6.0,-5.75) {\headingfont\fontsize{14pt}{16pt}\selectfont\textcolor{ink!45}{PHOTO}};\end{tikzpicture}\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent Then, in a beam of soft sunlight, the forest offered its jewel — the Common Green Magpie. Its emerald feathers glowed against the dark woods, eyes bright with curiosity, and tail gliding like a ribbon of light.
We watched in silent awe as it called out softly, vanishing back into the emerald shade. This fleeting moment stayed within — a reminder that nature's beauty often reveals itself in silence, just long enough to touch the soul.

\newpage

\section*{The Flame of Coorg}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Flame of Coorg}
\label{bird:5}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=11.5cm,keepaspectratio]{Vrathik2gb/Vrathik/14 s.jpg}\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent Nestled in the misty hills of Coorg, where coffee blossoms scent the air and streams sing softly through emerald valleys, nature reveals her finest art. On one such peaceful morning, camera in hand, I wandered through the dew-kissed woods, listening to awakening forest.

Amid the symphony of chirps and rustling leaves, a sudden flash of color caught my eyes the Flame-throated Bulbul, glowing like a spark of fire in the green mist. Its bright throat shone against the dark foliage, a living gem of the Western Ghats.\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent For a moment, the world stood still only the song of the bird, the whisper of the breeze, and the fragrance of Coorg's wild heart remained. In that silence, I felt the soul of nature itself.

Coorg's true beauty, I realized, is not just in its landscapes but in the little lives that fill its forests with music and light.

\newpage

\section*{The Song of the Hills – Birding Journey to Coorg}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Song of the Hills – Birding Journey to Coorg}
\label{bird:6}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent It was still dark when we began our journey from Puttur, our hearts filled with excitement for the day ahead. Our birding team — Suresh Kamat, Arun Santhosh, Venkatrya Malya, Avinash Adapa, and I — packed our breakfast and lunch, ready for a long day surrounded by nature's beauty. As the car climbed the winding Western Ghats, the cool mist hugged the hills, and the gentle sound of flowing streams followed us along the road.\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \begin{tikzpicture}\draw[dashed, line width=0.4pt, color=ink!35] (0,0) rectangle (12.0,-11.5);\node[anchor=center] at (6.0,-5.75) {\headingfont\fontsize{14pt}{16pt}\selectfont\textcolor{ink!45}{PHOTO}};\end{tikzpicture}\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent We stopped near a sparkling water stream in the ghat to enjoy our breakfast. The sound of rushing water, the chill of the morning breeze, and the first sun light touching the forest created a peaceful start to our adventure.

After breakfast, we continued toward our birding spot in Coorg, exploring the dense greenery and listening to the melodies of the forest. By noon, we had lunch amidst coffee plantations, the aroma of blossoms mixing with the earthy smell of rain-soaked soil.

As the evening golden sun light filled the woods, the forest gifted us two magical moments — a Flame-throated Bulbul, glowing like fire among the leaves, and later a              Grey-headed Bulbul, perched elegantly on a mossy branch.

Our photography in Coorg became more than just a birding trip. It was a story of friendship, patience, and the quiet joy of being one with nature — a reminder that true happiness takes flight when hearts travel together in the wild.

\newpage

\section*{The Jewel of Sattal}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Jewel of Sattal}
\label{bird:7}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=11.5cm,keepaspectratio]{Vrathik2gb/Vrathik/frame 93.jpg}\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent In the tranquil forests of Sattal, Uttarakhand, where sunlight filters softly through oak and pine, the morning began with a melody of wings. The forest was alive — every rustle, every chirp whispered the secrets of the Himalayas.

Then, from the shadowed bushes, emerged a burst of color — the Red-bellied Leiothrix, a tiny bird glowing with shades of gold, green, and scarlet. It perched gracefully on a mossy branch, as if nature herself had painted it with love.\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent Time just slowed down. The mist, the songs and the gentle eyes of that little bird reflected the very soul of Sattal — peaceful, vibrant, and divine.

\newpage

\section*{The Call of the Hills}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Call of the Hills}
\label{bird:8}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent In the misty valleys of Rong Tong, Darjeeling, the morning unfolded like a dream — clouds drifting low, hills wrapped in silence, and the scent of rain in the air. Alongside my birding friend Debpratim Shah, I wandered through the emerald slopes, camera ready, heart open to the wild.

Then, from the tall fig tree, came a sudden flutter — a magnificent Oriental Pied Hornbill appeared, its curved bill gleaming in the soft mountain light. With every call echoing through the valley, it felt as though the hills themselves were speaking.\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=11.5cm,keepaspectratio]{Vrathik2gb/Vrathik/s21.jpg}\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent The meeting of mist, mountain, and melody was magical. In its majestic flight, the hornbill carried the spirit of Darjeeling's forests — free, timeless, and full of grace.

\newpage

\section*{The Emerald in the Rain – Common Emerald Dove of Durga WLS, Karkala}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Emerald in the Rain – Common Emerald Dove of Durga WLS, Karkala}
\label{bird:9}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \begin{tikzpicture}\draw[dashed, line width=0.4pt, color=ink!35] (0,0) rectangle (12.0,-11.5);\node[anchor=center] at (6.0,-5.75) {\headingfont\fontsize{14pt}{16pt}\selectfont\textcolor{ink!45}{PHOTO}};\end{tikzpicture}\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent It was a soft, rainy morning inside the lush Durga Wildlife Sanctuary, Karkala. Along with Shivashankar Sir, Rajmohan, and Karthik Bhat, we wandered quietly through the dripping forest, our eyes searching for movement among the green.

Then, in the middle of a mossy tree, we saw it — a Common Emerald Dove, shimmering like a jewel in the rain. Tiny droplets clung to its feathers, glistening like pearls on green silk. The gentle patter of rain, the hush of the forest, and that radiant bird — it all came together in a perfect frame.\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent The emerald dove reminded us that beauty shines brightest when nature wears her simplest dress — rain, silence, and grace.

\newpage

\section*{The Whispering Song - Grey-headed Bulbul of Somvarpet, Coorg}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The Whispering Song - Grey-headed Bulbul of Somvarpet, Coorg}
\label{bird:10}
\vspace{0.5em}
\noindent
\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][t]{11.5cm}\justifying \noindent In the misty hills of Somvarpet, Coorg, the morning air was cool and filled with the fragrance of wild coffee flowers. Along with my birding friend Sathish Sarakki, I wandered through the wet leaves and soft breeze, listening to the melodies of the forest.

Then, on a slender branch, appeared a Grey-headed Bulbul — its olive-green body glowing softly against the mist, its grey crown glistening with dew. It sang a gentle tune, as if the forest itself was humming along. Every note carried the calm of Coorg's rain-wrapped beauty.\end{minipage}\hspace{0.8cm}\begin{minipage}[t][11.5cm][c]{12.0cm}\centering \includegraphics[width=12cm,height=11.5cm,keepaspectratio]{Vrathik2gb/Vrathik/frame 8.jpg}\end{minipage}
\newpage
\vspace*{0.3cm}
\noindent For a moment, everything else faded — only the bird, the mist, and the music remained. The Grey-headed Bulbul reminded us that peace doesn't shout; it sings softly in nature's voice.

\newpage

